ent: a conception of the unity of reason and an exploration of the powers it has to reach beyond itself and legislate over the world. With this in mind, Ferrarin dismantles the common vision of Kant as a philosopher writing separately on epistemology, ethics, and aesthetics and natural teleology, showing that the three Critiques are united by this underlying theme: the autonomy and teleology of reason, its power and ends. The result is a refreshing new view of Kant, and of reason itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPhilosophy. 0aReason. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  areasoning, thought, immanuel kant, philosophy, enlightenment, thinkers, epistemology, metaphysics, ethics, morality, aesthetics, western world, philosopher, the critique of pure reason, transcendental dialectic, teleology, kritik der praktischen vernunft, dichotomy, separation, cosmic, needs, knowledge, experience, possibility or impossibility, space, time, skepticism, cause and effect, appearance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022624315340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226243290423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226243290/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles